Q: Is there C++ syntax for &quot;at least one of these&quot; pure virtual methods? A: <blockquote>
<p>Is there C++ syntax for &quot;at least one of these&quot; pure virtual methods?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>No, there isn't (at least not at the moment, in standard C++).</p>
<p>One way to achieve what you need, would be to remove the default empty implementations from <code>http_resource</code>, and instead supply classes derived from it, that allow the user to implement only what they are interested in.</p>
<p>This is demonstrated below:</p>
<pre class="lang-cpp prettyprint-override"><code>//------ Your library classes:

struct http_resource {
    virtual void render_POST() = 0;
    virtual void render_GET() = 0;
};

// Derive from this class to implement POST:
struct http_resource_POST : public http_resource {
    virtual void render_GET() override {}  // default empty implementation of GET
};

// Derive from this class to implement GET:
struct http_resource_GET : public http_resource {
    virtual void render_POST() override {}  // default empty implementation of POST
};

//------ User classes:

// This class MUST implement render_POST():
struct user1 : public http_resource_POST {
    virtual void render_POST() override {}  
};

// This class MUST implement render_GET():
struct user2 : public http_resource_GET {
    virtual void render_GET() override {}
};

int main() {
    [[maybe_unused]] user1 u1;
    [[maybe_unused]] user2 u2;
}
</code></pre>
<p><kbd><a href="https://godbolt.org/z/rqxxz6zvT" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><strong>Live demo</strong></a></kbd></p>
<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A user class can also inherit both <code>http_resource_POST</code> and <code>http_resource_GET</code> to implement both.</li>
<li>This pattern can easily be extended to more than 2 virtual methods.</li>
</ol>

Q: How to implement EDATE() functionality of MS-excel in JAVASCRIPT A: <p>There is no such functionality, you have to build it by yourself.<br><br>
First I generate from your string a JS-date. From this I extract year, month and day.<br>
Than I sum the extramonths up and get the month by modulu 12 (months in JS are counted 0-11). If the months are negative I add 12 months up. For the year I add the integer part from monthSum didide through 12.<br>
If the day is greater or equal 29 and it's February and it's Leap year (year modulo 4 is 0) than the day is setted to 29. In all other cases the day is setted ton the minimum of privious day and the maximum of days in this month (stored in array MONTH).<br>
Now I have the desired date and I only format it for return: For getting the day with 2-digit add before the string &quot;0&quot; and then take the last 2 chars. For the abbreviation from the month I use the array MONTH.<br><br>
Try it out. I give you some critical examples with the Leap day and with negative/positive months which produces yearchange.</p>
<p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="false" data-console="true" data-babel="false" data-babel-preset-react="false" data-babel-preset-ts="false">
<div class="snippet-code">
<pre class="snippet-code-js lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>function edate(dateString, monthExtra) {
  const DAYS = [31, 28, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31];
  const MONTH = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'];

  let date = new Date(dateString);
  let year = date.getFullYear();
  let month = date.getMonth();
  let day = date.getDate();

  let monthSum = month + monthExtra;

  month = monthSum %12;
  if (month &lt; 0) {
    month = 12 + month;
  }

  year = year +  Math.floor(monthSum/12);

  if ( day&gt;=29 &amp;&amp; month==1 &amp;&amp; (year %4 == 0 )) {
    day = 29;
  } else {
    day = Math.min(day, DAYS[month]);
  }

  return ("0" + day).slice(-2) + '-' + MONTH[month] + '-' + year;
}

console.log(edate('06-Aug-2020', 13));
console.log(edate('30-Jan-2020', -13));
console.log(edate('30-Jan-2019', 1));
console.log(edate('29-Mar-2020', -13));</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</p>

Q: Mouse wheel scroll function is slow on exact page A: <p>We are facing the same issue after updating to the latest Chrome (94.0.4606.61, but someone else reported this happened from version 91), if your have a marquee on your page, it's very likely to make your mouse wheel scrolling slowly, and we believe it's Chrome's bug.</p>
