Q: Does it ever make sense to allow copies but no moves? A: <p>Perhaps you are overthinking this. Just because you don't know how to implement moves does not imply that you should disallow move semantics altogether. If your class cannot be moved it is sufficient to fall back to copies:</p>
<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;

struct foo {
    int f = 0;
    foo() = default;
    foo(const foo&amp; other) : f(other.f) { std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;copy\n&quot;; }
};

int main() {
    foo f;
    foo g = std::move(f); // prints: copy
}
</code></pre>
<blockquote>
<p>C++ Core Guideline C.64 suggests that a moved-from handle object whose t_ is equal to nullptr is fine</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It actually says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Ideally, that moved-from should be the default value of the type. Ensure that unless there is an exceptionally good reason not to.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It is unclear to my why the authors push so much for the default value. Anyhow, not having a default value (you say there is no default constructor), is an exceptionally good reason to not try to make a moved-from state equal the default value.</p>
<p>The moved-from object is supposed to be in a valid but otherwise unspecified state. From that perspective, either <code>other.t_ = nullptr;</code> or not doing it is both equally fine.</p>
<p>Summary: If you don't know how to move, just don't. Disallowing temporaries of your class is a different concern.</p>

Q: Fill v-combobox value with an API response A: <p>Bro the error usually happens because the API response isn't a direct array. Check the response structure:</p>
<pre><code>onMounted(async () =&gt; {
