Q: Unexpected end of JSON input / Unexpected token &#39;&lt;&#39; when using response.json() with fetch A: <p><code>response.ok === true</code> only means the HTTP status is in the 2xx range. It does not guarantee that the response body contains valid JSON.</p>
<p>In your case, the behavior is expected: <strong>202 Accepted</strong> often returns <strong>no response body</strong> → calling <code>response.json()</code> on an empty body throws <code>Unexpected end of JSON input</code>. <code>Unexpected token '&lt;'</code> means the response body is <strong>HTML</strong>, not JSON, commonly an SPA <code>index.html</code>, login page, redirect, or proxy error page. <code>fetch</code> does not validate response content — <code>response.json()</code> blindly tries to parse whatever it receives. That’s why <code>response.text()</code> works and shows HTML, while <code>response.json()</code> fails.</p>
<p><strong>The correct way to handle this is:</strong></p>
<p>Only parse JSON when the server actually returns JSON, and handle empty responses explicitly:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>const res = await fetch(url);

const contentType = res.headers.get(&quot;content-type&quot;) || &quot;&quot;;

if (res.status === 202 || res.status === 204) {
  return;
}

if (!contentType.includes(&quot;application/json&quot;)) {
  const text = await res.text();
  console.error(&quot;Expected JSON but got:&quot;, text);
  return;
}

const data = await res.json();
</code></pre>

Q: When is the renderer process in Electron application actually ready to listen for the events? A: <p>You are right, this is not <code>app.whenReady</code>.</p>
<p>But you should not use <code>await</code>. In the main-process Electron workflow, pretty much never. The asynchronous model is well-known and works correctly. Basically, this is what you do:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>const subscribeToEvents(window, /* ... */) =&gt; {
    // here, your main process can subscribe to events coming from renderer:
    ipcMain.on(someChannelName, /* data... */);
    ipcMain.on( /* and so on... */);
};

const createWindow = (title, /* ... */) =&gt; {
    //...
    const window = new BrowserWindow( /* ... */ );
    // from this moment, you can use IPC to communicate with the renderer:
    window.webContents.send(channelName, /* some data... */);
    // now, you can handle whatever happens when the web page has been rendered
    window.once('ready-to-show', () =&gt; {
       // send whatever should be handled right before showing
       // to the renderer to prepare it for showing:
       window.webContents.send(/* ... *);
       // here, window will be displayed without visual flash:
       window.show();
    }); //once ready to show
    // ...
    subscribeToEvents(window, /* ... */);
};

app.whenReady().then(() =&gt; {
    // some initialization to calculate title
    // and the options you need on createWindows
    createWindow(title, /* ... */);
    app.on(definitionSet.events.activate, () =&gt; {
    if (BrowserWindow.getAllWindows().length === 0)
        createWindow(title);
});
</code></pre>
<p>As you can see, the ultimate event when a renderer window can be shown is not <code>app.whenReady</code>, but <a href="https://www.electronjs.org/docs/latest/api/browser-window#event-ready-to-show" rel="nofollow noreferrer">'ready-to-show'</a>. Inside the handler of this event, your renderer process is ready to receive IPC events, so you have to use the 'ready-to-show' hander to do the initialization you need. Nevertheless, you also have to use the event <code>app.whenReady</code>, because the handler of this event is the place when you can create an instance (or instances) of the <a href="https://www.electronjs.org/docs/latest/api/browser-window" rel="nofollow noreferrer">BrowserWindow</a>.</p>

Q: PHP dependency injection and PSR LoggerInterface A: <p>Dependency injection framework differs in how object instances are instantiated. It mostly depends on the library you used as container. Symfony needs you to create <a href="https://symfony.com/doc/current/configuration.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">some YML configurations</a>. PHP-DI has its <a href="https://php-di.org/doc/php-definitions.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">own definition pattern</a>.</p>
<p>It is totally OK to create your own interface if you were to do all of the implementations anyway.</p>
<p>For example,</p>
<pre class="lang-php prettyprint-override"><code>interface MyLoggerFactoryInterface {
  public function log(string $message);
}

class MyTextLogger implements MyLoggerFactoryInterface {
  public function log(string $message) {
    echo $message;
  }
}

class MyHelloController {
  public function __construct(private MyLoggerFactoryInterface $logger) {
  }

  ...
  public function handleIndex() {
    ...
    $this-&gt;logger-&gt;log(&quot;something&quot;);
    ...
  }
}

// Assume you're using PHP DI (without autowiring)
$container = new DI\Container([
  MyTextLogger::class =&gt; create(),
  MyHelloController::class =&gt; create()-&gt;constructor(
     get(MyTextLogger::class), 
  ),
]);

...

$container-&gt;get(MyHelloController::class)-&gt;handleIndex();
</code></pre>

