Q: Is it possible to apply a single annotation to multiple use-site targets in Kotlin? A: <p>From Kotlin 2.2.0, experimental defaulting rule is added.</p>
<p>With the new rule, if there are multiple applicable targets, one or more is chosen as follows:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>If the constructor parameter target (<code>param</code>) is applicable, it is used.</p>
</li>
<li><p>If the property target (<code>property</code>) is applicable, it is used.</p>
</li>
<li><p>If the field target (<code>field</code>) is applicable while <code>property</code> isn't, <code>field</code> is used.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<pre class="lang-kotlin prettyprint-override"><code>data class User(
    val username: String,
    // @Email is now equivalent to @param:Email @field:Email
    @Email val email: String
) {
    // @Email is still equivalent to @field:Email
    @Email val secondaryEmail: String? = null
}
</code></pre>
<p>Check the docs</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://kotlinlang.org/docs/annotations.html#defaults-when-no-use-site-targets-are-specified" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://kotlinlang.org/docs/annotations.html#defaults-when-no-use-site-targets-are-specified</a></li>
</ul>

Q: SAS Mainframe ASA Carriage Control Behaviour A: <p>Hard to tell what you mean since you did not provide a working example program.</p>
<p>But I suspect you are talking about how the lines appear in the SAS log.  The data step will collapse adjacent empty lines.  It does not have anything to do with whether the first column is used to indicate carriage control.</p>
<p>Try this program</p>
<pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code>data _null_;
  PUT 'START';
  do i=1 to 10; PUT; end;
  PUT 'STOP' ;
run;

filename text temp ;
data _null_;
  file text ;
  PUT 'START';
  do i=1 to 10; PUT; end;
  PUT 'STOP' ;
run;
</code></pre>
<p>The first step will display this in the LOG.</p>
<pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code> START



 STOP
</code></pre>
<p>But when you look at the file generated by the second step you will see that all 10 empty lines are there.  (Note if you remove the _n_= from the PUT statement then SAS will again collapse the adjacent empty lines that the data _null_ step writes to the log.)</p>
<pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code> 85         data _null_;
