Q: Next.js 16 Partial Prerendering (PPR) + Cache Components: Why is my dynamic segment not streaming after first request? A: <p>The issue is caused by <code>export const revalidate = 3600</code> on the route segment — it applies ISR-style revalidation to the entire route, marking the cached dynamic component as potentially stale on every request, triggering a brief fallback flash and re-execution even within the 1-hour window.</p>
<p><strong>Fix:</strong> Remove the route-level <code>revalidate</code>. Then, inside <code>ProductData</code>, add <code>cacheLife('1h')</code> (or a custom profile) after <code>'use cache'</code> for explicit 1-hour caching:</p>
<pre><code>async function ProductData({ id }: { id: string }) {
  'use cache';
  cacheLife('1h');  // Controls stale/expire/revalidate for this cached component
  const product = await getProduct(id);
  return (/* ... */);
}
</code></pre>
<p>This caches the dynamic segment per <code>id</code> in the Data Cache. Subsequent visits (same id) serve the <strong>full page instantly</strong> (shell + filled dynamic content) with no flash or refetch.</p>
<p>For known/popular IDs, add <code>generateStaticParams()</code> to prerender them fully at build time.</p>
<p>This behavior is expected in Next.js 16 with Cache Components + PPR on dynamic routes; route-level <code>revalidate</code> overrides finer component caching.</p>

