Q: Unexpected end of JSON input / Unexpected token &#39;&lt;&#39; when using response.json() with fetch A: <p><code>response.ok === true</code> only means the HTTP status is in the 2xx range. It does not guarantee that the response body contains valid JSON.</p>
<p>In your case, the behavior is expected: <strong>202 Accepted</strong> often returns <strong>no response body</strong> → calling <code>response.json()</code> on an empty body throws <code>Unexpected end of JSON input</code>. <code>Unexpected token '&lt;'</code> means the response body is <strong>HTML</strong>, not JSON, commonly an SPA <code>index.html</code>, login page, redirect, or proxy error page. <code>fetch</code> does not validate response content — <code>response.json()</code> blindly tries to parse whatever it receives. That’s why <code>response.text()</code> works and shows HTML, while <code>response.json()</code> fails.</p>
<p><strong>The correct way to handle this is:</strong></p>
<p>Only parse JSON when the server actually returns JSON, and handle empty responses explicitly:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>const res = await fetch(url);

const contentType = res.headers.get(&quot;content-type&quot;) || &quot;&quot;;

if (res.status === 202 || res.status === 204) {
  return;
}

if (!contentType.includes(&quot;application/json&quot;)) {
  const text = await res.text();
  console.error(&quot;Expected JSON but got:&quot;, text);
  return;
}

const data = await res.json();
</code></pre>

