Q: CGI in Perl: how to access the original HTTP headers A: <p>CGI scripts don't receive HTTP requests; the receive CGI requests. But that in includes most of not all HTTP headers (depending on your server).</p>
<p>The request method is available as <code>$ENV{ REQUEST_METHOD }</code>.</p>
<p>The request uri is available as <code>$ENV{ REQUEST_URI }</code>.</p>
<p>Like you said, the Content-Type header is available as <code>$ENV{ CONTENT_TYPE }</code>.</p>
<p>Other headers Xxx-Yyy are (optionally) available as <code>$ENV{ HTTP_XXX_YYY }</code>.</p>
<p>Given the above, we can recreate the HTTP headers as follows:</p>
<pre class="lang-perl prettyprint-override"><code>sub cgi_to_http { $_[0] =~ s/^HTTP_//r =~ tr/_/-/r =~ s/\b\w+/\L\u$&amp;/gr }

my %headers =
   map { cgi_to_http( $_ ) =&gt; $ENV{ $_ } }
      grep { $_ eq &quot;CONTENT_TYPE&quot; or /^HTTP_/ }
         keys( %ENV );
</code></pre>
<p>The <code>s/\b\w+/\L\u$&amp;/g</code> part converts the capitalization of the key to its canon form. This is optional since HTTP headers are case-insensitive.</p>

